    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String name = null;
        System.out.println(name.length());
    }
}"

response:
You can fix the NullPointerException in the above Java code by checking if the object is null or not before invoking the method `length()` on it. Here's an updated version of the code that avoids the NullPointerException:

```java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String name = null;
        if (name != null) {
            System.out.println(name.length());
        } else {
            System.out.println("Name is null.");
        }
    }
}
```

In this updated version, we added an `if` statement to check if the `name` object is not null before invoking the `length()` method on it. If the `name` object is null, we print a message saying that "Name is null.". This modification ensures that the code does not throw a NullPointerException when the `name` object is null.

